base.author: markham
base.contents:
In extreme case, matrix has eigenvalue of 0 (M is not full rank). It's singular and can't be inverted at all.
Think about how matrix multiplication stretches space. When you perform it, your input is stretched a lot in one dimension and little in another; then when you invert, it amplifies the effect of the big-impact direction and minimizes the effect of the small-impact direction. So you're likelier to hit overflow or underflow.
Solution is "preconditioning": multiply by well conditioned matrix, perform your task, then multiply by inverse wellconditioned matrix
